**Similarity of Induced Weights.** All standard algorithms for linear regression estimate a weight vector \(\hat{\bm{w}}\). While neural ICL models like Transformers do not explicitly learn such a weight vector, similar to Akyurek et al. (2022), we can _induce_ an implicit weight vector \(\tilde{\bm{w}}\) learned by any algorithm \(\mathcal{A}\) by fitting a weight vector to its predictions. We can then measure similarity of algorithms by comparing the induced \(\tilde{\bm{w}}\). To do this, for any fixed sequence of \(t\) in-context examples \(\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t}\), we sample \(T\gg d\) query examples \(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{k}\stackrel{{\text{i.i.d.}}}{{\sim}}\mathcal{N}( \bm{0},\bm{\Sigma})\), where \(k\in[T]\). For this fixed sequence of in-context examples \(\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t}\), we create \(T\) in-context prediction tasks and use the algorithm \(\mathcal{A}\) to make predictions \(\mathcal{A}(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{k}\mid\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t})\). We define the induced data matrix and labels as

\[\tilde{\bm{X}}=\begin{bmatrix}\tilde{\bm{x}}_{1}^{\top}\\ \vdots\\ \tilde{\bm{x}}_{T}^{\top}\end{bmatrix}\qquad\tilde{\bm{Y}}=\begin{bmatrix} \mathcal{A}(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{1}\mid\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t})\\ \vdots\\ \mathcal{A}(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{T}\mid\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t})\end{bmatrix}.\] (7)

The induced weight vector for \(\mathcal{A}\) and these \(t\) examples is:

\[\tilde{\bm{w}}_{t}(\mathcal{A}):=\tilde{\bm{w}}_{t}(\mathcal{A} \mid\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t})=(\tilde{\bm{X}}^{\top}\tilde{\bm{X}})^{-1} \tilde{\bm{X}}^{\top}\tilde{\bm{Y}}.\] (8)

The similarity of induced weights between two algorithms \(\mathcal{A}_{a}\) and \(\mathcal{A}_{b}\) is the expected average cosine similarity3 of induced weights \(\tilde{\bm{w}}_{t}(\mathcal{A}_{a})\) and \(\tilde{\bm{w}}_{t}(\mathcal{A}_{b})\) over all possible \(1\leq t\leq n\), on a randomly sampled data sequence:

