#### a.2.3 Comparison with Other Second-Order Methods

In this section, we ablate with alternative second-order methods, such as Conjugate Gradient, BFGS, and its limited memory variant, L-BFGS.

**Conjugate Gradient Method.** For linear regression problems, the Conjugate Gradient (CG) method solves the linear system

\[\underbrace{(\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{X})}_{\bm{S}}\bm{w}-\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{y}=0\]

CG finds the weight vector \(\hat{\bm{w}}^{CG}\) with initialization \(\bm{w}_{0}\) by maintain a set of conjugate gradient \(\{\Delta\bm{w}_{1},\cdots,\Delta\bm{w}_{k}\}\). It follows the iterative update rule

\[\bm{d}_{k}=-\nabla\mathcal{L}(\bm{w}_{k})\] (12) \[\Delta\bm{w}_{k}=\bm{d}_{k}-\sum_{i=0}^{k-1}\frac{\bm{d}_{k}^{ \top}\bm{S}\Delta\bm{w}_{i}}{\Delta\bm{w}_{i}^{\top}\bm{S}\Delta\bm{w}_{i}} \Delta\bm{w}_{i}\] \[\alpha_{k}=\arg\min_{\alpha}\mathcal{L}(\bm{w}_{k}+\alpha\Delta \bm{w}_{k})\] \[\bm{w}_{k+1}=\bm{w}_{k}+\alpha_{k}\Delta\bm{w}_{k}\]

The conjugate Gradient method requires \(\mathcal{O}\left(\sqrt{\kappa}\log(1/\epsilon)\right)\) steps to converge to an \(\epsilon\) error on quadratic objectives such as linear regression.

**BFGS.** Broyden- Fletcher-Goldfarb-Shanno (BFGS) is a Quasi-Newton method, designed to approximate the inverse Hessian \(\bm{B}_{k}:\approx\nabla^{2}\mathcal{L}(\bm{w}_{k})^{-1}\). The BFGS updates are given by

\[\bm{w}_{k+1}=\bm{w}_{k}-\alpha_{k}\bm{B}_{k}\nabla\mathcal{L}(\bm{w}_{k})\] (13)

where

\[\bm{s}_{k} =\bm{w}_{k+1}-\bm{w}_{k}\] \[\bm{y}_{k} =\nabla\mathcal{L}(\bm{w}_{k+1})-\nabla\mathcal{L}(\bm{w}_{k})\] \[\bm{B}_{k+1} =\bm{B}_{k}-\frac{\bm{B}_{k}\bm{y}_{k}\bm{y}_{k}^{\top}\bm{B}_{k} }{\bm{y}_{k}^{\top}\bm{B}_{k}\bm{y}_{k}}+\frac{\bm{s}_{k}\bm{s}_{k}^{\top}}{ \bm{y}_{k}^{\top}\bm{s}_{k}}\]

When \(k\) is large, \(\bm{B}_{k}\) approximates the inverse Hessian well.

**L(imited-memory)-BFGS.** L-BFGS is a limited-memory version of BFGS. Instead of the inverse Hessian \(\bm{B}_{k}\), L-BFGS maintains a history of past \(m\) updates (where \(m\) is usually small). Recall the iterative update rule of \(\bm{B}_{k}\) in BFGS

\[\bm{B}_{k+1}=\bm{B}_{k}-\frac{\bm{B}_{k}\bm{y}_{k}\bm{y}_{k}^{\top}\bm{B}_{k} }{\bm{y}_{k}^{\top}\bm{B}_{k}\bm{y}_{k}}+\frac{\bm{s}_{k}\bm{s}_{k}^{\top}}{ \bm{y}_{k}^{\top}\bm{s}_{k}}\] (14)

Unlike BFGS, which recursively unroll to an initialization \(\bm{B}_{0}\), L-BFGS only unroll to \(\bm{B}_{k-m}\) but replacing \(\bm{B}_{k-m}\) with \(\bm{B}_{\mathrm{init}}\). In this regard, running \(n\) steps of L-BFGS only requires \(\mathcal{O}(mn)\) memory, which is more memory-efficient than BFGS who requires \(\mathcal{O}(n^{2})\) memory. The trade-off is that L-BFGS won't have a good estimate of the inverse Hessian when \(m<d\), where \(d\) is the dimensionality of the quadratic problem. In this regard, it will converge slower than full BFGS.

In Figure 11 and Figure 12, we compare Transformers with BFGS, L-BFGS, and Conjugate Gradient method on the metric of similarity of errors. We find that Transformers have a similar _linear_ correspondence with BFGS. This is perhaps not surprising, given that BFGS also gets a superlinear convergence rate for linear regression Nocedal and Wright (1999). Meanwhile, Transformers show a substantially faster convergence rate than L-BFGS and CG.

