Detailed Proofs for Section 5

In this section, we work on full attention layers with normalized ReLU activation \(\sigma(\cdot)=\frac{1}{n}\mathrm{ReLU}(\cdot)\) given \(n\) examples.

**Definition B.1**.: A full attention layer with \(M\) heads and ReLU activation is also denoted as \(\mathrm{Attn}\) on any input sequence \(\bm{H}=[\bm{h}_{1},\cdots,\bm{h}_{N}]\in\mathbb{R}^{D\times N}\), where \(D\) is the dimension of hidden states and \(N\) is the sequence length. In the vector form,

\[\tilde{\bm{h}}_{t}=[\mathrm{Attn}(\bm{H})]_{t}=\bm{h}_{t}+\frac{1}{n}\sum_{m=1} ^{M}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\mathrm{ReLU}\left(\left(\bm{Q}_{m}\bm{h}_{t},\bm{K}_{m}\bm{h }_{j}\right)\right)\cdot\bm{V}_{m}\bm{h}_{j}\] (18)

_Remark B.2_.: This is slightly different from the **causal** attention layer (see Definition 3.1) in that at each time stamp \(t\), the attention layer in Definition B.1 has full information of all hidden states \(j\in[n]\), unlike causal attention layer which requires \(j\in[t]\).

### Helper Results

We begin by constructing a useful component for our proof, and state some existing constructions from Akyurek et al. (2022).

**Lemma B.3**.: _Given hidden states \(\{\bm{h}_{1},\cdots,\bm{h}_{n}\}\), there exists query, key and value matrices \(\bm{Q},\bm{K},\bm{V}\) respectively such that one attention layer can compute \(\sum_{j=1}^{n}\bm{h}_{j}\)._

Proof.: We can pad each hidden state by \(1\) and \(0\)'s such that \(\bm{h}^{\prime}_{t}\leftarrow\begin{bmatrix}\bm{h}_{t}\\ 1\\ \bm{0}_{d}\end{bmatrix}\in\mathbb{R}^{2d+1}\). We construct two heads where \(\bm{Q}_{1}=\bm{K}_{1}=\bm{Q}_{2}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{Q}_{d\times d}&\bm{O}_{d \times 1}&\bm{O}_{d\times d}\\ \bm{O}_{1\times d}&1&\bm{O}_{1\times d}\\ \bm{O}_{d\times d}&\bm{O}_{d\times 1}&\bm{O}_{d\times d}\end{bmatrix}\) and \(\bm{K}_{2}=-\bm{K}_{1}\). Then

\[\begin{bmatrix}\bm{O}_{d\times d}&\bm{O}_{d\times 1}&\bm{O}_{d\times d}\\ \bm{O}_{1\times d}&1&\bm{O}_{1\times d}\\ \bm{O}_{d\times d}&\bm{O}_{d\times 1}&\bm{O}_{d\times d}\end{bmatrix}\bm{h}^{ \prime}_{t}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{0}_{d}\\ 1\\ \bm{0}_{d}\end{bmatrix}.\]

Let \(\bm{V}_{1}=\bm{V}_{2}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{O}_{(d+1)\times d}&\bm{O}_{(d+1) \times(d+1)}\\ n\bm{I}_{d\times d}&\bm{O}_{d\times(d+1)}\end{bmatrix}\) so that \(\bm{V}_{m}\begin{bmatrix}\bm{h}_{j}\\ 1\\ \bm{0}_{d}\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{0}_{d+1}\\ n\bm{h}_{j}\end{bmatrix}\).

We apply one attention layer to these 1-padded hidden states and we have

\[\tilde{\bm{h}}_{t} =\bm{h}^{\prime}_{t}+\frac{1}{n}\sum_{m=1}^{2}\sum_{j=1}^{n} \mathrm{ReLU}\left(\left\langle\bm{Q}_{m}\bm{h}^{\prime}_{t},\bm{K}_{m}\bm{h }^{\prime}_{j}\right\rangle\right)\cdot\bm{V}_{m}\bm{h}^{\prime}_{j}\] (19) \[=\bm{h}^{\prime}_{t}+\frac{1}{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left[\mathrm{ReLU} (1)+\mathrm{ReLU}(-1)\right]\cdot\begin{bmatrix}\bm{0}_{d+1}\\ n\bm{h}_{j}\end{bmatrix}\] \[=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{h}_{t}\\ 1\\ \bm{0}_{d}\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}\bm{0}_{d+1}\\ \sum_{j=1}^{n}\bm{h}_{j}\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{h}_{t}\\ 1\\ \sum_{j=1}^{n}\bm{h}_{j}\end{bmatrix}\]

**Proposition B.4** (Akyurek et al., 2022).: _Each of_ mov, aff, mul, div _can be implemented by a single transformer layer. These four operations are mappings \(\mathbb{R}^{D\times N}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{D\times N}\), expressed as follows,_

\(\mathtt{mov}(\bm{H};s,t,i,j,i^{\prime},j^{\prime})\)_: selects the entries of the \(s\)-th column of \(\bm{H}\) between rows \(i\) and \(j\), and copies them into the \(t\)-th column (\(t\geq s\)) of \(\bm{H}\) between rows \(i^{\prime}\) and \(j^{\prime}\)._

\(\mathtt{mul}(\bm{H};a,b,c,(i,j),(i^{\prime},j^{\prime}),(i^{\prime\prime},j^{ \prime\prime}))\)_: in each column \(\bm{h}\) of \(\bm{H}\), interprets the entries between \(i\) and \(j\) as an \(a\times b\) matrix \(\bm{A}_{1}\), and the entries between \(i^{\prime}\) and \(j^{\prime}\) as a \(b\times c\) matrix \(\bm{A}_{2}\), multiplies these matrices together, and stores the result between rows \(i^{\prime\prime}\) and \(j^{\prime\prime}\), yielding a matrix in which each column has the form \(\left[\bm{h}_{:i^{\prime\prime}-1},\bm{A}_{1}\bm{A}_{2},\bm{h}_{j^{\prime \prime}}\right]^{\top}\). This allows the layer to implement inner products._\(\texttt{div}(\bm{H};(i,j),i^{\prime},(i^{\prime\prime},j^{\prime\prime}))\): in each column \(\bm{h}\) of \(\bm{H}\), divides the entries between \(i\) and \(j\) by the absolute value of the entry at \(i^{\prime}\), and stores the result between rows \(i^{\prime\prime}\) and \(j^{\prime\prime}\), yielding a matrix in which every column has the form \([\bm{h}_{:i^{\prime\prime}-1},\bm{h}_{i:j}/|\bm{h}_{i^{\prime}}|,\bm{h}_{j^{ \prime\prime}}]^{\top}\)._

\(\texttt{aff}(\bm{H};(i,j),(i^{\prime},j^{\prime}),(i^{\prime\prime},j^{ \prime\prime}),\bm{W}_{1},\bm{W}_{2},\mathbf{b})\)_: in each column \(\bm{h}\) of \(\bm{H}\), applies an affine transformation to the entries between \(i\) and \(j\) and \(i^{\prime}\) and \(j^{\prime}\), then stores the result between rows \(i^{\prime\prime}\) and \(j^{\prime\prime}\), yielding a matrix in which every column has the form \([\bm{h}_{:i^{\prime\prime}-1},\bm{W}_{1}\bm{h}_{i:j}+\bm{W}_{2}\bm{h}_{i^{ \prime}:j^{\prime}}+\mathbf{b},\bm{h}_{j^{\prime\prime}}]^{\top}\). This allows the layer to implement subtraction by setting \(\bm{W}_{1}=\bm{I}\) and \(\bm{W}_{2}=-\bm{I}\)._

### Proof of Theorem 5.1

**Theorem 5.1**.: _For any \(k\), there exist Transformer weights such that on any set of in-context examples \(\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n}\) and test point \(\bm{x}_{\rm test}\), the Transformer predicts on \(\bm{x}_{\rm test}\) using \(\bm{x}_{\rm test}^{\top}\hat{\bm{w}}_{k}^{\rm Newton}\). Here \(\hat{\bm{w}}_{k}^{\rm Newton}\) are the Iterative Newton updates given by \(\hat{\bm{w}}_{k}^{\rm Newton}=\bm{M}_{k}\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{y}\) where \(\bm{M}_{j}\) is updated as_

\[\bm{M}_{j}=2\bm{M}_{j-1}-\bm{M}_{j-1}\bm{S}\bm{M}_{j-1},1\leq j\leq k,\quad \bm{M}_{0}=\alpha\bm{S},\]

_for some \(\alpha>0\) and \(\bm{S}=\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{X}\). The dimensionality of the hidden layers is \(\mathcal{O}(d)\), and the number of layers is \(k+8\). One transformer layer computes one Newton iteration. 3 initial transformer layers are needed for initializing \(\bm{M}_{0}\) and 5 layers at the end are needed to read out predictions from the computed pseudo-inverse \(\bm{M}_{k}\)._

Proof.: We break the proof into parts.

**Transformers Implement Initialization \(\bm{T}^{(0)}=\alpha\bm{S}\).** Given input sequence \(\bm{H}:=\{\bm{x}_{1},\cdots,\bm{x}_{n}\}\), with \(\bm{x}_{i}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\), we first apply the mov operations given by Proposition B.4 (similar to Akyurek et al. (2022), we show only non-zero rows when applying these operations):

\[\begin{bmatrix}\bm{x}_{1}&\cdots&\bm{x}_{n}\end{bmatrix}\stackrel{{ \rm mov}}{{\longrightarrow}}\begin{bmatrix}\bm{x}_{1}&\cdots&\bm{x}_{n}\\ \bm{x}_{1}&\cdots&\bm{x}_{n}\end{bmatrix}\] (20)

We call each column after mov as \(\bm{h}_{j}\). With an full attention layer, one can construct two heads with query and value matrices of the form \(\bm{Q}_{1}^{\top}\bm{K}_{1}=-\bm{Q}_{2}^{\top}\bm{K}_{2}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{I} _{d\times d}&\bm{O}_{d\times d}\\ \bm{O}_{d\times d}&\bm{O}_{d\times d}\end{bmatrix}\) such that for any \(t\in[n]\), we have

\[\sum_{m=1}^{2}\mathrm{ReLU}\left(\langle\bm{Q}_{m}\bm{h}_{t},\bm{K}_{m}\bm{h} _{j}\rangle\right)=\mathrm{ReLU}(\bm{x}_{t}^{\top}\bm{x}_{j})+\mathrm{ReLU}(- \bm{x}_{t}^{\top}\bm{x}_{j})=\langle\bm{x}_{t},\bm{x}_{j}\rangle\] (21)

Let all value matrices \(\bm{V}_{m}=n\alpha\begin{bmatrix}\bm{I}_{d\times d}&\bm{O}_{d\times d}\\ \bm{O}_{d\times d}&\bm{O}_{d\times d}\end{bmatrix}\) for some \(\alpha\in\mathbb{R}\). Combining the skip connections, we have

\[\tilde{\bm{h}}_{t}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{x}_{t}\\ \bm{x}_{t}\end{bmatrix}+\frac{1}{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left\langle\bm{x}_{t},\bm{x} _{j}\right\rangle n\alpha\begin{bmatrix}\bm{x}_{j}\\ \bm{0}\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{x}_{t}\\ \bm{x}_{t}\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}\alpha\left(\sum_{j=1}^{n}\bm{x}_{j}\bm{ x}_{j}^{\top}\right)\bm{x}_{t}\\ \bm{0}\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{x}_{t}+\alpha\bm{S}\bm{x}_{t}\\ \bm{x}_{t}\end{bmatrix}\] (22)

Now we can use the aff operator to make subtractions and then

\[\begin{bmatrix}\bm{x}_{t}+\alpha\bm{S}\bm{x}_{t}\\ \bm{x}_{t}\end{bmatrix}\stackrel{{\rm aff}}{{\longrightarrow}} \begin{bmatrix}(\bm{x}_{t}+\alpha\bm{S}\bm{x}_{t})-\bm{x}_{t}\\ \bm{x}_{t}\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\alpha\bm{S}\bm{x}_{t}\\ \bm{x}_{t}\end{bmatrix}\] (23)

We call this transformed hidden states as \(\bm{H}^{(0)}\) and denote \(\bm{T}^{(0)}=\alpha\bm{S}\):

\[\bm{H}^{(0)}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{h}_{1}^{(0)}&\cdots&\bm{h}_{n}^{(0)}\end{bmatrix}= \begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(0)}\bm{x}_{1}&\cdots&\bm{T}^{(0)}\bm{x}_{n}\\ \bm{x}_{1}&\cdots&\bm{x}_{n}\end{bmatrix}\] (24)

Notice that \(\bm{S}\) is symmetric and thereafter \(\bm{T}^{(0)}\) is also symmetric.

**Transformers implement Newton Iteration.** Let the input prompt be the same as Equation (24),

\[\bm{H}^{(0)}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{h}_{1}^{(0)}&\cdots&\bm{h}_{n}^{(0)}\end{bmatrix}= \begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(0)}\bm{x}_{1}&\cdots&\bm{T}^{(0)}\bm{x}_{n}\\ \bm{x}_{1}&\cdots&\bm{x}_{n}\end{bmatrix}\] (25)We claim that the \(\ell\)'s hidden states can be of the similar form

\[\bm{H}^{(\ell)}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{h}_{1}^{(\ell)}&\cdots&\bm{h}_{n}^{(\ell)} \end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{1}&\cdots&\bm{T}^{(\ell)} \bm{x}_{n}\\ \bm{x}_{1}&\cdots&\bm{x}_{n}\end{bmatrix}\] (26)

We prove by induction that assuming our claim is true for \(\ell\), we work on \(\ell+1\):

Let \(\bm{Q}_{m}=\tilde{\bm{Q}}_{m}\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\bm{Q}_{d}&-\frac{n} {2}\bm{I}_{d}\\ \bm{Q}_{d}&\bm{Q}_{d}\end{bmatrix}}_{\bm{G}}\), \(\bm{K}_{m}=\tilde{\bm{K}}_{m}\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\bm{I}_{d}&\bm{O}_{d} \\ \bm{O}_{d}&\bm{O}_{d}\end{bmatrix}}_{\bm{J}}\) where \(\tilde{\bm{Q}}_{1}^{\top}\tilde{\bm{K}}_{1}:=\bm{I}\), \(\tilde{\bm{Q}}_{2}^{\top}\tilde{\bm{K}}_{2}:=-\bm{I}\) and \(\bm{V}_{1}=\bm{V}_{2}=\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\bm{I}_{d}&\bm{O}_{d}\\ \bm{O}_{d}&\bm{O}_{d}\end{bmatrix}}_{\bm{J}}\). A 2-head self-attention layer, with ReLU attentions, can be written has

\[\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell+1)}=[\operatorname{Attn}(\bm{H}^{(\ell)})]_{t}=\bm{h}_{t}^{( \ell)}+\frac{1}{n}\sum_{m=1}^{2}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\operatorname{ReLU}\left( \left\langle\bm{Q}_{m}\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell)},\bm{K}_{m}\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)} \right\rangle\right)\cdot\bm{V}_{m}\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)}\] (27)

where

\[\begin{split}&\sum_{m=1}^{2}\operatorname{ReLU}\left(\left\langle \bm{Q}_{m}\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell)},\bm{K}_{m}\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)}\right\rangle \right)\cdot\bm{V}_{m}\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)}\\ &=\begin{bmatrix}\operatorname{ReLU}\left((\bm{G}\bm{h}_{t}^{( \ell)})^{\top}\underbrace{\tilde{\bm{Q}}_{1}^{\top}\tilde{\bm{K}}_{1}}(\bm{J} \bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)})\right)+\operatorname{ReLU}\left((\bm{G}\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell )})^{\top}\underbrace{\tilde{\bm{Q}}_{2}^{\top}\tilde{\bm{K}}_{2}}(\bm{J}\bm{h }_{j}^{(\ell)})\right)\end{bmatrix}\cdot(\bm{J}\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)})\\ &=\begin{bmatrix}\operatorname{ReLU}((\bm{G}\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell)})^{\top}(\bm{ J}\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)}))+\operatorname{ReLU}(-(\bm{G}\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell)})^{\top}(\bm{J} \bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)}))\end{bmatrix}\cdot(\bm{J}\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)})\\ &=(\bm{G}\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell)})^{\top}(\bm{J}\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)})(\bm{J}\bm{h}_{ j}^{(\ell)})\\ &=(\bm{J}\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)})(\bm{J}\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)})^{\top}(\bm{G}\bm{h}_{ t}^{(\ell)})\end{split}\] (28)

Plug in our assumptions that \(\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{j}\\ \bm{x}_{j}\end{bmatrix}\), we have \(\bm{J}\bm{h}_{j}^{(\ell)}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{j}\\ \bm{0}_{d}\end{bmatrix}\) and \(\bm{G}\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell)}=\begin{bmatrix}-\frac{n}{2}\bm{x}_{t}\\ \bm{0}_{d}\end{bmatrix}\), we have

\[\begin{split}\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell+1)}&=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{( \ell)}\bm{x}_{t}\\ \bm{x}_{t}\end{bmatrix}+\frac{1}{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)} \bm{x}_{j}\\ \bm{0}_{d}\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{j}\\ \bm{0}_{d}\end{bmatrix}^{\top}\begin{bmatrix}-\frac{n}{2}\bm{x}_{t}\\ \bm{0}_{d}\end{bmatrix}\\ &=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{t}-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{j=1}^{n}(\bm{T}^{( \ell)}\bm{x}_{j})(\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{j})^{\top}\bm{x}_{t}\end{bmatrix}\\ &\bm{x}_{t}\\ &=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{t}-\frac{1}{2}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\left(\sum_ {j=1}^{n}\bm{x}_{j}\bm{x}_{j}^{\top}\right)\bm{T}^{(\ell)}{}^{\top}\bm{x}_{t} \end{bmatrix}\\ &\bm{x}_{t}\\ &=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}-\frac{1}{2}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{S}\bm{T}^{(\ell )}{}^{\top}\end{bmatrix}\bm{x}_{t}\end{bmatrix}\\ &=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}-\frac{1}{2}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{S}\bm{T}^{(\ell )}{}^{\top}\end{bmatrix}\bm{x}_{t}\end{bmatrix}\] (29)

Now we pass over an MLP layer with

\[\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell+1)}\leftarrow\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell+1)}+\begin{bmatrix}\bm{I}_{d}& \bm{O}_{d}\\ \bm{O}_{d}&\bm{O}_{d}\end{bmatrix}\bm{h}_{t}^{(\ell+1)}=\begin{bmatrix}\left(2 \bm{T}^{(\ell)}-\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{S}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}{}^{\top}\right)\bm{x}_{t} \end{bmatrix}\] (30)

Now we denote the iteration

\[\bm{T}^{(\ell+1)}=2\bm{T}^{(\ell)}-\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{S}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}{}^{\top}\] (31)

We find that \(\bm{T}^{(\ell+1)}{}^{\top}=\bm{T}^{(\ell+1)}\) since \(\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\) and \(\bm{S}\) are both symmetric. It reduces to

\[\bm{T}^{(\ell+1)}=2\bm{T}^{(\ell)}-\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{S}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\] (32)

This is exactly the same as the Newton iteration.

**Transformers can implement \(\hat{\bm{w}}_{\ell}^{\mathrm{TF}}=\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{y}\).** Going back to the empirical prompt format \(\{\bm{x}_{1},y_{1},\cdots,\bm{x}_{n},y_{n}\}\). We can let parameters be zero for positions of \(y\)'s and only rely on the skip connection up to layer \(\ell\), and the \(\bm{H}^{(\ell)}\) is then \(\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{j}&\bm{0}\\ \bm{x}_{j}&\bm{0}\\ 0&y_{j}\end{bmatrix}_{j=1}^{n}\). We again apply operations from Proposition B.4:

\[\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{j}&\bm{0}\\ \bm{x}_{j}&\bm{0}\\ 0&y_{j}\end{bmatrix}_{j=1}^{n}\xrightarrow{\mathrm{mov}}\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T} ^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{j}&\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{j}\\ \bm{x}_{j}&\bm{0}\\ 0&y_{j}\end{bmatrix}_{j=1}^{n}\xrightarrow{\mathrm{mul}}\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T} ^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{j}&\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{j}\\ \bm{x}_{j}&\bm{0}\\ 0&y_{j}\\ \bm{0}&\bm{T}^{(\ell)}y_{j}\bm{x}_{j}\end{bmatrix}_{j=1}^{n}\] (33)

