\[\mathrm{Output}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\begin{bmatrix}\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{j}\\ \bm{0}\\ y_{j}\\ \bm{T}^{(\ell)}y_{j}\bm{x}_{j}\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{\xi}\\ \bm{T}^{(\ell)}\sum_{j=1}^{n}y_{j}\bm{x}_{j}\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{ \xi}\\ \bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{y}\end{bmatrix}\] (34)

where \(\bm{\xi}\) denotes irrelevant quantities. Note that the resulting \(\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{y}\) is also the same as Iterative Newton's predictor \(\hat{\bm{w}}_{k}=\bm{M}_{k}\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{y}\) after \(k\) iterations. We denote \(\hat{\bm{w}}_{\ell}^{\mathrm{TF}}=\bm{T}^{(\ell)}\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{y}\).

**Transformers can make predictions on \(\bm{x}_{test}\) by \(\big{\langle}\hat{\bm{w}}_{\ell}^{\mathrm{TF}},\bm{x}_{\mathrm{test}}\big{\rangle}\).**

Now we can make predictions on text query \(\bm{x}_{\mathrm{test}}\):

\[\begin{bmatrix}\bm{\xi}&\bm{x}_{\mathrm{test}}\\ \hat{\bm{w}}_{\ell}^{\mathrm{TF}}&\bm{x}_{\mathrm{test}}\end{bmatrix} \xrightarrow{\mathrm{mov}}\begin{bmatrix}\bm{\xi}&\bm{x}_{\mathrm{test}}\\ \hat{\bm{w}}_{\ell}^{\mathrm{TF}}&\bm{x}_{\mathrm{test}}\\ \bm{0}&\hat{\bm{w}}_{\ell}^{\mathrm{TF}}\\ 0&\big{\langle}\hat{\bm{w}}_{\ell}^{\mathrm{TF}},\bm{x}_{\mathrm{test}}\big{\rangle} \end{bmatrix}\] (35)

Finally, we can have an readout layer \(\bm{\beta}_{\mathrm{ReadOut}}=\{\bm{u},v\}\) applied (see Definition 3.3) with \(\bm{u}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{0}_{3d}&1\end{bmatrix}^{\top}\) and \(v=0\) to extract the prediction \(\big{\langle}\hat{\bm{w}}_{\ell}^{\mathrm{TF}},\bm{x}_{\mathrm{test}}\big{\rangle}\) at the last location, given by \(\bm{x}_{\mathrm{test}}\). This is exactly how Iterative Newton makes predictions.

**To Perform \(k\) steps of Newton's iterations, Transformers need \(\mathcal{O}(k)\) layers.**

Let's count the layers:

* **Initialization**: \(\mathtt{mov}\) needs \(\mathcal{O}(1)\) layer; gathering \(\alpha\bm{S}\) needs \(\mathcal{O}(1)\) layer; and \(\mathtt{aff}\) needs \(\mathcal{O}(1)\) layer. In total, Transformers need \(\mathcal{O}(1)\) layers for initialization.
* **Newton Iteration**: each exact Newton's iteration requires \(\mathcal{O}(1)\) layer. Implementing \(k\) iterations requires \(\mathcal{O}(k)\) layers.
* **Implementing \(\hat{\bm{w}}_{\ell}^{\mathrm{TF}}\)**: We need one operation of \(\mathtt{mov}\) and \(\mathtt{mul}\) each, requiring \(\mathcal{O}(1)\) layer each. Apply Lemma B.3 for summation also requires \(\mathcal{O}(1)\) layer.
* **Making prediction on test query**: We need one operation of \(\mathtt{mov}\) and \(\mathtt{mul}\) each, requiring \(\mathcal{O}(1)\) layer each.

Hence, in total, Transformers can implement \(k\)-step Iterative Newton and make predictions accordingly using \(\mathcal{O}(k)\) layers. 

_Remark B.5_.: We note that Giannou et al. (2023) used 13 layers to compute one Newton Iteration, and in our construction, we need only one Transformer layer (with one attention layer and one MLP layer) to compute one Newton Iteration. At the same time, we didn't use Akyurek et al. (2022) for constructing Newton Iterations. Akyurek et al. (2022) is applied to initialize Newton and for reading out the prediction.

In our construction, only the initialization and read-out prediction components use causal attention and softmax because Akyurek et al. (2022)'s construction is applied. To be more specific, those are the first 3 layers in initializing Iterative Newton and the last 5 layers in reading out the predictions from the computed pseudo-inverse. All the layers corresponding to the Iterative Newton updates are using full attention and normalized ReLU activations.

