### Iterative Newton as a Sum of Moments Method

Recall that Iterative Newton's method finds \(\bm{S}^{\dagger}\) as follows

\[\bm{M}_{0}=\underbrace{\frac{2}{\|\bm{S}\bm{S}^{\top}\|_{2}}}_{\alpha}\bm{S}^ {\top},\qquad\bm{M}_{k}=2\bm{M}_{k-1}-\bm{M}_{k-1}\bm{S}\bm{M}_{k-1},\forall k \geq 1.\] (37)

We can expand the iterative equation to moments of \(\bm{S}\) as follows.

\[\bm{M}_{1}=2\bm{M}_{0}-\bm{M}_{0}\bm{S}\bm{M}_{0}=2\alpha\bm{S}^{\top}-4 \alpha^{2}\bm{S}^{\top}\bm{S}\bm{S}^{\top}=2\alpha\bm{S}-4\alpha^{2}\bm{S}^{3}.\] (38)

Let's do this one more time for \(\bm{M}_{2}\).

\[\bm{M}_{2} =2\bm{M}_{1}-\bm{M}_{1}\bm{S}\bm{M}_{1}=2(2\alpha\bm{S}-4\alpha^{ 2}\bm{S}^{3})-(2\alpha\bm{S}-4\alpha^{2}\bm{S}^{3})\bm{S}(2\alpha\bm{S}-4 \alpha^{2}\bm{S}^{3})\] (39) \[=4\alpha\bm{S}-8\alpha^{2}\bm{S}^{3}-4\alpha^{2}\bm{S}^{3}+16 \alpha^{3}\bm{S}^{5}-16\alpha^{4}\bm{S}^{7}\] \[=4\alpha\bm{S}-12\alpha^{2}\bm{S}^{3}+16\alpha^{3}\bm{S}^{5}-16 \alpha^{4}\bm{S}^{7}.\]

We can see that \(\bm{M}_{k}\) are summations of moments of \(\bm{S}\), with respect to some pre-defined coefficients from the Newton's algorithm. Hence Iterative Newton is a special of an algorithm which computes an approximation of the inverse using second-order moments of the matrix,

\[\bm{M}_{k}=\sum_{s=1}^{2^{k+1}-1}\beta_{s}\bm{S}^{s}\] (40)

with coefficients \(\beta_{s}\in\mathbb{R}\).

We note that Transformer circuits can represent other sum of moments other than Newton's method. We can introduce different coefficients \(\beta_{i}\) than in the proof of Theorem 5.1 by scaling the value matrices or through the MLP layers.

### Estimated weight vectors lie in the span of previous examples

What properties can we infer and verify for the weight vectors which arise from Newton's method? A straightforward one arises from interpreting any sum of moments method as a kernel method.

We can expand \(\bm{S}^{s}\) as follows

\[\bm{S}^{s}=\left(\sum_{i=1}^{t}\bm{x}_{i}\bm{x}_{i}^{\top}\right)^{s}=\sum_{i=1} ^{t}\left(\sum_{j_{1},\cdots,j_{s-1}}\left\langle\bm{x}_{i},\bm{x}_{j_{1}} \right\rangle\prod_{v=1}^{s-2}\left\langle\bm{x}_{j_{v}},\bm{x}_{j_{s+1}} \right\rangle\right)\bm{x}_{i}\bm{x}_{j_{s-1}}^{\top}.\] (41)

Then we have

\[\hat{\bm{w}}_{t} =\bm{M}_{t}\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{y}=\sum_{s=1}^{2^{t+1}-1}\beta_{s}\bm {S}^{s}\bm{X}^{\top}\bm{y}\] (42) \[=\sum_{s=1}^{2^{t+1}-1}\beta_{s}\left\{\sum_{i=1}^{t}\left(\sum_ {j_{1},\cdots,j_{s-1}}\left\langle\bm{x}_{i},\bm{x}_{j_{1}}\right\rangle\prod _{v=1}^{s-2}\left\langle\bm{x}_{j_{v}},\bm{x}_{j_{v+1}}\right\rangle\right) \bm{x}_{i}\bm{x}_{j_{s-1}}^{\top}\right\}\left\{\sum_{i=1}^{t}y_{i}\bm{x}_{i}\right\}\] \[=\sum_{s=1}^{2^{t+1}-1}\beta_{s}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{t}\left(\sum_{j _{1},\cdots,j_{s}}y_{j_{s}}\left\langle\bm{x}_{i},\bm{x}_{j_{1}}\right\rangle \prod_{v=1}^{s-1}\left\langle\bm{x}_{j_{v}},\bm{x}_{j_{v+1}}\right\rangle \right)\bm{x}_{i}\right)\] \[=\sum_{i=1}^{t}\underbrace{\left(\sum_{s=1}^{2^{t+1}-1}\sum_{j_{1 },\cdots,j_{s}}\beta_{s}y_{j_{s}}\left\langle\bm{x}_{i},\bm{x}_{j_{1}}\right\rangle \prod_{v=1}^{s-1}\left\langle\bm{x}_{j_{v}},\bm{x}_{j_{v+1}}\right\rangle \right)}_{\phi_{t}(i\mid\bm{X},\bm{y},\bm{\beta})}\bm{x}_{i}\] \[=\sum_{i=1}^{t}\phi_{t}(i\mid\bm{X},\bm{y},\bm{\beta})\:\bm{x}_{i}\]

where \(\bm{X}\) is the data matrix, \(\bm{\beta}\) are coefficients of moments given by the sum of moments method and \(\phi_{t}(\cdot)\) is some function which assigns some weight to the \(i\)-th datapoint, based on all other datapoints. Therefore if the Transformer implements a sum of moments method (such as Newton's method), then its induced weight vector \(\tilde{\bm{w}}_{t}(\mathrm{Transformers}\mid\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t})\) after seeing in-context examples \(\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t}\) should lie in the span of the examples \(\{\bm{x}_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t}\):

\[\tilde{\bm{w}}_{t}(\mathrm{Transformers}\mid\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t}) \stackrel{{?}}{{=}}\mathrm{Span}\{\bm{x}_{1},\cdots,\bm{x}_{t}\}= \sum_{t=1}^{t}a_{i}\bm{x}_{i}\qquad\text{for coefficients $a_{i}$}.\] (43)

We test this hypothesis. Given a sequence of in-context examples \(\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t}\), we fit coefficients \(\{a_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t}\) in Equation (43) to minimize MSE loss:

\[\{\hat{a}_{i}\}_{i=1}^{t}=\operatorname*{arg\,min}_{a_{1},a_{2},\cdots,a_{t} \in\mathbb{R}}\left\|\tilde{\bm{w}}_{t}(\mathrm{Transformers}\mid\{\bm{x}_{i},y_{ i}\}_{i=1}^{t})-\sum_{t=1}^{t}a_{i}\bm{x}_{i}\right\|_{2}^{2}.\] (44)

We then measure the quality of this fit across different number of in-context examples \(t\), and visualize the residual error in Figure 27. We find that even when \(t<d\), Transformers' induced weights still lie close to the span of the observed examples \(\bm{x}_{i}\)'s. This provides an additional validation of our proposed mechanism.

